kes a person happy, healthy, successful and fulfilled.</p>\r\n<p>I was born in a small town just south of Richmond, Virginia, in the United States. My mother was a schoolteacher for one of the local schools. I believe she taught English and writing, but it all seems so vague now. Today, she is retired and tutors to keep busy. My dad, on the other hand, when I was I born was a journalist for the Richmond newspaper. Since then he has become a columnist for the same newspaper, but he is also an author. I am very proud to say that I come from a family of smart, happy, successful people who have always excelled at what they do.</p>\r\n<p>But there is more to me than my family. I am a person of my own experiences and dreams, hopes, and letdowns. I don&rsquo;t come from a wealthy family &ndash; in fact, we&rsquo;ve struggled financially over the years, just like other middle-class families. Nothing has ever been fed to me on a silver platter. Like my parents, I&rsquo;ve worked very hard, even at only 21 years old, for the things I&rsquo;ve accomplished in life. I&rsquo;m very proud of this fact.</p>\r\n<p>I am lucky in that my parents have taught me so much knowledge about the real world. Over the years they have helped me find people &ndash; friends and co-workers mostly &ndash; who would let me volunteer with them and learn about their job, doing short-served internships of sorts. Those experiences in high school and college have led me to my current course of study: Marketing. I have learned, from a very young and impressionable age, that our economic system is Capitalism: an economic and political system in which a country\'s trade and industry are controlled by private owners for profit, rather than by the state. Our country is run on the trading and selling of goods that are on a supply-and-demand basis, so it is important to market a product so that the public wants to buy and then does buy it. Marketing is ubiquitous and needed for every industry and market. Word-of-mouth advertising, of course, is effective, but it is nowhere near as helpful in turning profit as marketing.</p>\r\n<p>The term &ldquo;Marketing&rdquo; is indeed a vague one. It means advertising or promoting something, or as in offering for sale. It is done through advertisements on billboards, TV, radio, print publications, online publications, etc. Marketing is also done through the media &ndash; as in articles and stories about people, businesses, and products. When I graduate I will be prepared to start a career in the field, which will always be needed and adaptable to weak or strong economies. My focus will be in digital advertising as a way to market something. This involves many important and much-needed skills. Selling would involve superb language and communication skills, as well as superb interpersonal and listening skills. A salesman or saleswoman has to ease into learning of selling of their product or service, I&rsquo;ve learned. (In summer between semesters in college, I did a short stint selling advertisements in the community newspaper; it was a very helpful experience. I did well and made some spending money, but I also learned how to talk to people and sell.) Meeting with a potential client, on a sales call, is a lot like the hybrid of a job interview and auditioning for a role in a play. You need to know your lines, or at least be prepared to read aloud and use notes as a prompt. My goal is to own an advertising agency which will help big businesses, like Fortunate 500 businesses, market their products or services. I have a lot to learn, but I&rsquo;m certainly on my way to getting there.</p>','Essay About Yourself Sample: Adam Koontz Tells about Himself','','publish','closed','closed','','essay-about-yourself-example','','','2017-05-17 09:28:55','2017-05-17 06:28:55','',0,'',0,'page','',0),(376,1,'2015-11-17 17:57:13','2015-11-17 15:57:13','','essay-about-yourself3-v3','','inherit','closed','closed','','essay-about-yourself3-v3','','','2017-05-17 09:28:55','2017-05-17 06:28:55','',375,'https://ozessay-a.akamaihd.net/content/3/en/images/articles/essay-about-yourself3-v3.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpg',0),(377,1,'2015-11-27 18:14:53','2015-11-27 16:14:53','<p style=\"text-align: left;\">With season five of AMC&rsquo;s hit show The Walking Dead having concluded in the spring of 2015, one must reflect on how the zombie-horror genre has come to be so prominent in American popular culture. Not only has there been numerous films, novels, and television shows &ndash; both mainstream and underground &ndash; on the subject, there are even &ldquo;zombie-infested&rdquo; 5K&rsquo;s happening around the country and all around the world. Though The Walking Dead attracts millions of weekly viewers and will mostly likely be back for another season soon, most of the fans of the zombie-horror genre &ndash; besides the hardcore horror fanatics &ndash; probably don&rsquo;t know the true origin and history of the zombie legend.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">The Oxford English Dictionary states that the origin of the zombie myth can be traced back to West Africa. First recorded in the English language in 1819, the word &ldquo;zombie&rdquo; is the product of a Congo language, linguistically evolving from the Kikongo words &ldquo;zumbi&rdquo; (translated as &ldquo;fetish&rdquo;). &ldquo;Zombie&rdquo; was also originally used to reference a snake-god of the West African voodoo religion. &ldquo;When these peoples were taken as slaves to Haiti and other parts of the Caribbean during the 18th and early 19th centuries, they brought their religious beliefs and practices with them,&rdquo; (&ldquo;What is the origin&hellip;&rdquo;). UC Irvine professor Amy Wilentz believes the zombie genre to be a &ldquo;very logical offspring of New World slavery,&rdquo; (qt. in Gandhi). The institution of slavery in Haiti was so cruel, says Wilentz, that, to the slave, death was the only real escape.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">Suicide was the slave\'s only way to take control over his or her own body ... And yet, the fear of becoming a zombie might stop them from doing so ... This final rest &mdash; in green, leafy, heavenly Africa, with no sugarcane to cut and no master to appease or serve &mdash; is unavailable to the zombie. To become a zombie was the slave\'s worst nightmare: to be dead and still a slave, an eternal field hand. (qt. in Gandhi.)</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">Zombies and slavery have been associated with one another in the United States since it first appeared in &ldquo;The Unknown Painter,&rdquo; a short story that was first published in the Chamber&rsquo;s Edinburgh Journal and subsequently reprinted in the American Alton Telegraph in 1838. The story, according to an essay on the evolution of the zombie in popular culture, was evidently popular among the American readers, with many different versions of the story printed in local newspapers across the country. Maximilian Schele de Vere, a linguistic scholar, would later define a zombie as \"a phantom or a ghost, not infrequently heard in the Southern States in nurseries and among the servants,\" (qt. in Gandhi).</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">In 1929, the word found its way into the American mainstream culture after author William Seabrook wrote a book, The Magic Island, about the voodoo worshippers he &ldquo;witnessed&rdquo; in Haiti &ndash; with numerous film scholars holding that White Zombie, a 1932 horror film, was based upon the work of Seabrook. George Romero&rsquo;s 1968 classic Night of the Living Dead is now considered a staple in the zombie-horror genre. Not only did it introduce zombie-horror to audiences worldwide, it became a social commentary on the racial tension of the 1960s in America as Romero cast Duane Jones, a black actor, as the film&rsquo;s hero.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">This craze is certainly entering the mainstream, and to conclude, here is a perfect example of how it is becoming part of mainstream American society: Recently, the Center for Disease Control and Prevention attempted to exploit the zombie craze by publishing a page on their website concerned with &ldquo;zombie preparedness.&rdquo; Dr. Ali Khan, the Director of the Office of Public Health Preparedness and Response, states, &ldquo;If you are generally well-equipped to deal with a zombie apocalypse, you will be prepared for a hurricane, pandemic, earthquake or terrorist attack,\" (qt. in Gandhi). Due to its popularity, the page crashed soon after posting, (Gandhi).</p>','Free Sample Essay About Zombies','','publish','closed','closed','','essay-about-zombies','','','2017-05-17 12:59:52','2017-05-17 09:59:52','',0,'',0,'page','',0),(378,1,'2015-11-27 18:14:53','2015-11-27 16:14:53','','free_sample_essay_about_zombies_ozessay','','inherit','closed','closed','','free_sample_essay_about_zombies_ozessay','','','2017-05-17 12:59:52','2017-05-17 09:59:52','',377,'https://ozessay-a.akamaihd.net/images/article/og/free_sample_essay_about_zombies_ozessay.jpg?v=1495701344',0,'attachment','image/jpg',0),(379,1,'2015-12-04 13:38:50','2015-12-04 11:38:50','<p dir=\"rtl\">?? ????? ????? ?? ??????? ???? ?? ?????? ????? ?? ??????? ????????. ????? ?????????? ???????? ?????? ?? ?????? ?? ???? ?????. ???? ????? ?? ???? ?? ??? ?? ???????? ?? ???? ??????? ?? ??? ???????? ????. ??? ?? ???? ????? ?????? ??? ?? ???? ????? ???? ???? ???????. ????? ?????? ????? ????? ???? ??????? ???? ??????.</p>\r\n<h2 dir=\"rtl\">?? ?? ????? ?????</h2>\r\n<p dir=\"rtl\">??? ????? ???? ???? ??????? ????? ????? ?? ???? ???? ???? ?? ??????? ??? ???? ?? ????? ?? ??? ?? ???? ????? ??????. ??? ????? ??????? ???? ???? ?????? ?????.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"rtl\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"rtl\">??????? ?????????? ?? ???? ?????? ???? ??? ???? ?????? ????? ?? ?????? ?????. ????? ?? ???? ???? ?????? ????. ??? ???? ?????? ???? ????? ?? ????? ?? ?????? ??????? ?? ?????. ?? ????? ??? ??? ????. ?????? ?????? ????? ?? ?? ???? ????? ????